#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:3
msgid "Doctest integration for modules and test files"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:5
msgid ""
"By default all files matching the ``test*.txt`` pattern will be run through "
"the python standard ``doctest`` module.  You can change the pattern by "
"issuing:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:9
msgid "pytest --doctest-glob='*.rst'"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:13
msgid ""
"on the command line. ``--doctest-glob`` can be given multiple times in the "
"command-line."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:15
msgid "If you then have a text file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:17
msgid ""
"# content of test_example.txt\n"
"\n"
"hello this is a doctest\n"
">>> x = 3\n"
">>> x\n"
"3"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:26
msgid "then you can just invoke ``pytest`` directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:28
msgid ""
"$ pytest\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 1 item\n"
"\n"
"test_example.txt .                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================ 1 passed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:41
msgid ""
"By default, pytest will collect ``test*.txt`` files looking for doctest "
"directives, but you can pass additional globs using the ``--doctest-glob`` "
"option (multi-allowed)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:44
msgid ""
"In addition to text files, you can also execute doctests directly from "
"docstrings of your classes and functions, including from test modules:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:47
msgid ""
"# content of mymodule.py\n"
"def something():\n"
"    \"\"\" a doctest in a docstring\n"
"    >>> something()\n"
"    42\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    return 42"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:57
msgid ""
"$ pytest --doctest-modules\n"
"=========================== test session starts "
"============================\n"
"platform linux -- Python 3.x.y, pytest-5.x.y, py-1.x.y, pluggy-0.x.y\n"
"cachedir: $PYTHON_PREFIX/.pytest_cache\n"
"rootdir: $REGENDOC_TMPDIR\n"
"collected 2 items\n"
"\n"
"mymodule.py .                                                        [ 50%]\n"
"test_example.txt .                                                   [100%]\n"
"\n"
"============================ 2 passed in 0.12s ============================="
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:71
msgid ""
"You can make these changes permanent in your project by putting them into a "
"pytest.ini file like this:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:74
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.ini\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"addopts = --doctest-modules"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:82
msgid ""
"The builtin pytest doctest supports only ``doctest`` blocks, but if you are "
"looking for more advanced checking over *all* your documentation, including "
"doctests, ``.. codeblock:: python`` Sphinx directive support, and any other "
"examples your documentation may include, you may wish to consider `Sybil "
"<https://sybil.readthedocs.io/en/latest/index.html>`__. It provides pytest "
"integration out of the box."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:91
msgid "Encoding"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:93
msgid ""
"The default encoding is **UTF-8**, but you can specify the encoding that "
"will be used for those doctest files using the ``doctest_encoding`` ini "
"option:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:97
msgid ""
"# content of pytest.ini\n"
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_encoding = latin1"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:104
msgid "Using 'doctest' options"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:106
msgid ""
"Python's standard ``doctest`` module provides some `options <https://docs."
"python.org/3/library/doctest.html#option-flags>`__ to configure the "
"strictness of doctest tests. In pytest, you can enable those flags using the "
"configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:110
msgid ""
"For example, to make pytest ignore trailing whitespaces and ignore lengthy "
"exception stack traces you can just write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:113
msgid ""
"[pytest]\n"
"doctest_optionflags= NORMALIZE_WHITESPACE IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:118
msgid ""
"Alternatively, options can be enabled by an inline comment in the doc test "
"itself:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:121
msgid ""
">>> something_that_raises()  # doctest: +IGNORE_EXCEPTION_DETAIL\n"
"Traceback (most recent call last):\n"
"ValueError: ..."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:127
msgid "pytest also introduces new options:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:129
msgid ""
"``ALLOW_UNICODE``: when enabled, the ``u`` prefix is stripped from unicode "
"strings in expected doctest output. This allows doctests to run in Python 2 "
"and Python 3 unchanged."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:133
msgid ""
"``ALLOW_BYTES``: similarly, the ``b`` prefix is stripped from byte strings "
"in expected doctest output."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:136
msgid ""
"``NUMBER``: when enabled, floating-point numbers only need to match as far "
"as the precision you have written in the expected doctest output. For "
"example, the following output would only need to match to 2 decimal places::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:140
msgid ""
">>> math.pi\n"
"3.14"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:143
msgid ""
"If you wrote ``3.1416`` then the actual output would need to match to 4 "
"decimal places; and so on."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:146
msgid ""
"This avoids false positives caused by limited floating-point precision, like "
"this::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:149
msgid ""
"Expected:\n"
"    0.233\n"
"Got:\n"
"    0.23300000000000001"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:154
msgid ""
"``NUMBER`` also supports lists of floating-point numbers -- in fact, it "
"matches floating-point numbers appearing anywhere in the output, even inside "
"a string! This means that it may not be appropriate to enable globally in "
"``doctest_optionflags`` in your configuration file."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:163
msgid "Continue on failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:165
msgid ""
"By default, pytest would report only the first failure for a given doctest. "
"If you want to continue the test even when you have failures, do:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:168
msgid "pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-continue-on-failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:174
msgid "Output format"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:176
msgid ""
"You can change the diff output format on failure for your doctests by using "
"one of standard doctest modules format in options (see :data:`python:doctest."
"REPORT_UDIFF`, :data:`python:doctest.REPORT_CDIFF`, :data:`python:doctest."
"REPORT_NDIFF`, :data:`python:doctest.REPORT_ONLY_FIRST_FAILURE`):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:181
msgid ""
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report none\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report udiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report cdiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report ndiff\n"
"pytest --doctest-modules --doctest-report only_first_failure"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:191
msgid "pytest-specific features"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:193
msgid ""
"Some features are provided to make writing doctests easier or with better "
"integration with your existing test suite. Keep in mind however that by "
"using those features you will make your doctests incompatible with the "
"standard ``doctests`` module."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:198
msgid "Using fixtures"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:200
msgid "It is possible to use fixtures using the ``getfixture`` helper:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:202
msgid ""
"# content of example.rst\n"
">>> tmp = getfixture('tmpdir')\n"
">>> ...\n"
">>>"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:209
msgid ""
"Also, :ref:`usefixtures` and :ref:`autouse` fixtures are supported when "
"executing text doctest files."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:216
msgid "'doctest_namespace' fixture"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:218
msgid ""
"The ``doctest_namespace`` fixture can be used to inject items into the "
"namespace in which your doctests run. It is intended to be used within your "
"own fixtures to provide the tests that use them with context."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:222
msgid ""
"``doctest_namespace`` is a standard ``dict`` object into which you place the "
"objects you want to appear in the doctest namespace:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:225
msgid ""
"# content of conftest.py\n"
"import numpy\n"
"\n"
"\n"
"@pytest.fixture(autouse=True)\n"
"def add_np(doctest_namespace):\n"
"    doctest_namespace[\"np\"] = numpy"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:235
msgid "which can then be used in your doctests directly:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:237
msgid ""
"# content of numpy.py\n"
"def arange():\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    >>> a = np.arange(10)\n"
"    >>> len(a)\n"
"    10\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    pass"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:248
msgid ""
"Note that like the normal ``conftest.py``, the fixtures are discovered in "
"the directory tree conftest is in. Meaning that if you put your doctest with "
"your source code, the relevant conftest.py needs to be in the same directory "
"tree. Fixtures will not be discovered in a sibling directory tree!"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:253
msgid "Skipping tests dynamically"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:257
msgid "You can use ``pytest.skip`` to dynamically skip doctests. For example:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../doc/en/doctest.rst:259
msgid ""
">>> import sys, pytest\n"
">>> if sys.platform.startswith('win'):\n"
"...     pytest.skip('this doctest does not work on Windows')\n"
"..."
msgstr ""
